Dictionaries & Pandas¶

Dictionaries, Part 1¶

Motivation for dictionaries¶

This is the long way using two lists. This is not efficient.

In [245]:
# Definition of countries and capital
countries = ['spain', 'france', 'germany', 'norway']
capitals = ['madrid', 'paris', 'berlin', 'oslo']

# Get index of 'germany': ind_ger
ind_ger = countries.index('germany')

# Use ind_ger to print out capital of Germany
print(capitals[ind_ger])

berlin

Create dictionary¶

In [246]:
# Definition of countries and capital
countries = ['spain', 'france', 'germany', 'norway']
capitals = ['madrid', 'paris', 'berlin', 'oslo']

# From string in countries and capitals, create dictionary europe
europe = {'spain':'madrid',
          'france':'paris',
          'germany':'berlin', 
          'norway':'oslo'}

# Print europe
print(europe)

{'spain': 'madrid', 'france': 'paris', 'germany': 'berlin', 'norway': 'oslo'}

Access dictionary¶

Just use the key as the index

In [247]:
# Print out the keys in europe
print(europe.keys())

# Print out value that belongs to key 'norway'
print(europe['norway'])

dict_keys(['spain', 'france', 'germany', 'norway'])
oslo

Dictionaries, Part 2¶

  • if you add two of the same keys to a dictionary, only the last one will be kept
  • keys must be immutable objects.
    • i.e. the key can't be a list.
    • but you can use a string, boolean, or integer

Pandas, Part 1¶

  • Its very common to have many variables of different types for an observation
    • i.e. you may have country name, area, population, and true or false for something
    • Here a 2D nupy array is not an option to store all of the data because it can only have data of one type. Its more like a matrix. What we need is a data frame. Hello Pandas.
  • Pandas is build on numpy

Dictionary to DataFrame (1)¶

In [254]:
# Pre-defined lists
names = ['United States', 'Australia', 'Japan', 'India', 'Russia', 'Morocco', 'Egypt']
dr =  [True, False, False, False, True, True, True]
cpc = [809, 731, 588, 18, 200, 70, 45]

# pandas is already imported

# Create dictionary my_dict with three key:value pairs: my_dict
my_dict = {
    'country': names,
    'drives_right': dr,
    'cars_per_cap': cpc
    }

# Build a DataFrame cars from my_dict: cars
cars = pd.DataFrame(my_dict)

# Print cars
print(cars)

Pandas, Part 2¶

  • Row labels are important for indexing in pandas
  • You can use double brackets to select columns or single to select a slice of rows
    • But this is all a bit limited.
  • loc and iloc are much more verstile for selecting parts of a dataframe
    • loc is the pandas way to select based on labels
    • iloc is for integer position-based selection
    • this is similar to using my_array[rows, columns] indexing with numpy arrays
    • still need to use double brackets the have the data in a dataframe or display
    • you can select rows and columns at the same time

Boolean operators with Numpy¶

  • and, or, and not do not work on numpy arrays
  • Instead use the functions locigal_and(), locigal_or(), locigal_not()
In [286]:
# Create arrays
my_house = np.array([18.0, 20.0, 10.75, 9.50])
your_house = np.array([14.0, 24.0, 14.25, 9.0])
In [287]:
# my_house greater than 18.5 or smaller than 10
print(np.logical_or(my_house > 18.5, my_house < 10))

[False  True False  True]
In [288]:
# Both my_house and your_house smaller than 11
print(np.logical_and(my_house < 11, your_house < 11))

[False False False  True]

Random Walk¶

Here is an example with 10 coin flips: This example is not a 'walk' because the value of the current step is not based on the previous steps.

In [322]:
np.random.seed(123)
outcomes = []
for x in range(10):
    coin = np.random.randint(0,2)
    if coin == 0:
        outcomes.append("heads")
    else:
        outcomes.append("tails")
print(outcomes)

['heads', 'tails', 'heads', 'heads', 'heads', 'heads', 'heads', 'tails', 'tails', 'heads']

In this case we do use a random walk because the current value depends on what happened before. Here we simply keep track of the total number of tails.

In [323]:
np.random.seed(123)
tails = [0]
for x in range(10):
    coin = np.random.randint(0,2)
    tails.append(tails[x] + coin)
print(tails)

[0, 0, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 1, 2, 3, 3]

The next step¶

In [324]:
np.random.seed(123)

# Initialize random_walk
random_walk = [0]

# Complete the ___
for x in range(100) :
    # Set step: last element in random_walk
    step = random_walk[-1]

    # Roll the dice
    dice = np.random.randint(1,7)

    # Determine next step
    if dice <= 2:
        step = step - 1
    elif dice <= 5:
        step = step + 1
    else:
        step = step + np.random.randint(1,7)

    # append next_step to random_walk
    random_walk.append(step)

# Print random_walk
print(random_walk)

How low can you go?¶

Here we just fix the code below using max() so that you can't go below floor 0.

In [325]:
np.random.seed(123)

# Initialize random_walk
random_walk = [0]

for x in range(100) :
    step = random_walk[-1]
    dice = np.random.randint(1,7)

    if dice <= 2:
        # Replace below: use max to make sure step can't go below 0
        step = max(0, step - 1)
    elif dice <= 5:
        step = step + 1
    else:
        step = step + np.random.randint(1,7)

    random_walk.append(step)

print(random_walk)

Distribution¶

Distribution of tails count from 10 coin flips...

In [327]:
np.random.seed(123)
final_tails = []
for x in range(10000):
    tails = [0]
    for x in range(10):
        coin = np.random.randint(0,2)
        tails.append(tails[x] + coin)
    final_tails.append(tails[-1])
plt.hist(final_tails, bins = 10)
plt.show()

The more times you simulate the 10 coin flips, the closer you get to the theoretical bell curve distributions. At 10,000 this is getting pretty close.

Visualize all walks¶

np.random.seed(123)
all_walks = []

for i in range(10) :
    random_walk = [0]
    for x in range(100) :
        step = random_walk[-1]
        dice = np.random.randint(1,7)
        if dice <= 2:
            step = max(0, step - 1)
        elif dice <= 5:
            step = step + 1
        else:
            step = step + np.random.randint(1,7)
        random_walk.append(step)
    all_walks.append(random_walk)

# Convert all_walks to Numpy array: np_aw
np_aw = np.array(all_walks)

# Plot np_aw and show
plt.plot(np_aw)
plt.show()

# Clear the figure
plt.clf()

# Transpose np_aw: np_aw_t
np_aw_t = np.transpose(np_aw)

# Plot np_aw_t and show
plt.plot(np_aw_t)
plt.show()

Implement clumsiness¶

In [330]:
np.random.seed(123)
all_walks = []

# Simulate random walk 250 times
for i in range(250) :
    random_walk = [0]
    for x in range(100) :
        step = random_walk[-1]
        dice = np.random.randint(1,7)
        if dice <= 2:
            step = max(0, step - 1)
        elif dice <= 5:
            step = step + 1
        else:
            step = step + np.random.randint(1,7)

        # Implement clumsiness
        if np.random.rand() <= 0.001 :
            step = 0

        random_walk.append(step)
    all_walks.append(random_walk)

# Create and plot np_aw_t
np_aw_t = np.transpose(np.array(all_walks))
plt.plot(np_aw_t)
plt.show()
